    "#### Dominant Data Characteristics\n",
    " \n",
    "From the inspection above, five characteristics shape our algorithm and preprocessing choices:\n",
    " \n",
    "1. **Mixed data types** — Roughly half numerical, half categorical. All categorical features must be encoded to numerical form before distance-based algorithms can run, using different strategies for ordinal vs. nominal vs. multi-value types.\n",
    " \n",
    "2. **High dimensionality after encoding** — One-hot encoding 6 nominal features (~22 categories) plus 9 binary columns from multi-value parsing will expand the feature space from 19 to ~35–40 dimensions. This risks diluting distance signals (curse of dimensionality), making PCA worth exploring.\n",
    " \n",
    "3. **Skewed and zero-inflated features** — `Vehicle Monthly Distance Km` is heavily right-skewed (skewness = 1.48) with a large spike at 0 for non-drivers. Log-transformation should be applied before scaling.\n",
    " \n",
    "4. **Structural missingness** — `Vehicle Type` is missing for 67% of respondents by design (non-drivers). This must be encoded as \"none,\" not imputed or dropped.\n",
    " \n",
    "5. **Scale differences** — Ranges vary from 0–9,999 (vehicle distance) to 1–7 (waste bag count). StandardScaler is essential so no single feature dominates distance calculations."
